, 30 fairies flew away. Therefore, Katelyn's friend's count of fairies is half the original count of fairies. Therefore, the number of remaining fairies is 30.": 1, "Question: Katelyn saw 50 fairies fly above the nearby forest.\nReasoning: Katelyn saw 50 fairies flying above the nearby forest.\nWorking for 20 minutes, Katelyn saw half as many fairies as Katelyn saw come from the east and join the fairies that were there.\nTherefore, 20/50 = 50 fairies remaining.\n\nQuestion: While playing with her friends in their school playground, one of Katelyn's friends saw half as many fairies as Katelyn saw come from the east and join the fairies that were there.\nReasoning:\n\n1. Katelyn's friend saw half as many fairies as Katelyn saw come from the east and join the fairies that were there.\n2. After 20 minutes, her friend saw half as many fairies as Katelyn saw come from the east and join the fairies that were there.\n\nTherefore, 20/50 = 50 fairies remaining.\n\nQuestion: Betty is saving money for a new wallet which costs $100. Betty has only half of the money she needs. Her parents decided to give her $15 for that purpose, and her grandparents twice as much as her parents. How much more money does Betty need to buy the wallet?\n\nReasoning:\n\n1. In the beginning, Betty has only 100 / 2 = $<<100/2=50>>50.\n2. Betty's grandparents gave her 15 * 2 = $<<15*2=30>>30.\n3.": 1}
