[self_consistency][tinyllama_1_1b_chat][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 3/5 answer='Question: Craig and his brother take turns spelling out the longest letter words they know and counting the number of the letters in those words. After ten rounds, Craig has spelled out 20 words with 15 letters each. If Craig\'s brother has spelled words with a total count of letters 50 more than Craig, calculate the total number of letters in the words they\'ve spelled after the ten rounds.\n\nReasoning:\nCraig and his brother have been spelling out the longest letter words they know in a row. Each round, Craig spells out the next longest letter word (i.e., "Z" in "ZZZZZZZ") with 15 letters, and his brother spells out the next longest letter word (i.e., "F" in "FFFFF") with 50 more letters than Craig.\n\nThe total number of letters in the words they\'ve spelled thus far is:\n- 20 words, each with 15 letters\n- 15 letters, each spelled by Craig\n- 50 more letters, each spelled by his brother\n\nTherefore, the total number of letters in the words they\'ve spelled after ten rounds is:\n- 20 words, each with 15 letters\n- 15 letters, each spelled by Craig\n- 50 more letters, each spelled by his brother\n\n- 50 more letters, each spelled by his brother\n= 100\n\nTherefore, the total number of letters in the words they\'ve spelled thus far and after ten rounds is:\n- 20 words, each with 15 letters\n- 15 letters, each spelled by Craig\n-'
