[self_consistency][tinyllama_1_1b_chat][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 4/5 answer='Question: Craig and his brother take turns spelling out the longest letter words they know and counting the number of the letters in those words. After ten rounds, Craig has spelled out 20 words with 15 letters each. If Craig\'s brother has spelled words with a total count of letters 50 more than Craig, calculate the total number of letters in the words they\'ve spelled after the ten rounds.\n\nReasoning:\n\nCraig and his brother\'s total count of letters for the first ten rounds is 20.\n\nCraig\'s brother spells out the longest letter word they know, "B", with a count of 21 letters.\n\nThe total number of letters in the words Craig and his brother have spelled after ten rounds is:\n\nCraig: 20 letters\nCraig\'s brother: 21 letters\n\nTherefore, the total number of letters in the words Craig and his brother have spelled after ten rounds is:\n\nCraig: 20 + 21 = 41\nCraig\'s brother: 21 + 21 = 42\n\nTherefore, the total number of letters in the words Craig and his brother have spelled after ten rounds is:\n\nCraig: 41 + 42 = 83\nCraig\'s brother: 42 + 42 = 84\n\nTherefore, the total number of letters in the words Craig and his brother have spelled after ten rounds is:\n\nCraig: 83 + 84 = 167\nCraig\'s brother: 84 + 84 = 16'
